<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900411-0014</DOCNO><DOCID>900411-0014.</DOCID><HL>   What's News:   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>04/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   THE THRIFT BAILOUT AGENCY flopped in its second attempt tosell 40-year bonds, a sign that investors aren't ready forbonds that have extra-long maturities. The $3.5 billionauction of so-called &quot;bailout bonds&quot; went poorly despite ahigher-than-expected average yield of 8.89%.                                                                                                       </LP><TEXT>   Treasury-bond prices tumbled in reaction to the Sandamp;L bondauction. Stocks edged higher, while the dollar fell againstthe mark and yen.   ---   William Farley plans to surrender majority ownership ofWest Point-Pepperell because he is unable to pay for the$1.56 billion acquisition. The move follows last year'sbitter takeover battle with the textile giant.   ---   Lockheed's board easily won its proxy battle againstDallas investor Harold Simmons. But a slate of Simmons-backedinitiatives also was approved, signaling holders want moresay in the defense firm's revival.   ---   The Big Three auto makers are expected to post a 70% dropin first-quarter earnings, reflecting efforts to clearbloated inventories. The strategy included a 26.5% reductionin quarterly production and sales incentives averaging $1,000a vehicle.   ---   Merrill Lynch has tightened its grip on how it creditsinvestors' securities proceeds, which could save the firmmillions of dollars that had gone to clients. Merrill brokersare complaining about the move, though it is practiced byother big brokerages.   ---   Bell Atlantic said its Bell of Pennsylvania phone unitagreed to pay $42 million to settle charges it used&quot;deceptive techniques&quot; to sell customers more services thanthey wanted.   ---   Eastern Airlines' unsecured creditors asked a bankruptcycourt to remove the carrier's management and appoint atrustee to run the troubled Texas Air subsidiary.   ---   Credit Suisse's parent is discussing an alliance with BankLeu, paving the way for a long-awaited consolidation of theSwiss banking market.   ---   Two Mitsubishi Group firms plan to reunite despiteexpected criticism that they are trying to re-establish theirprewar monopoly in Japan.   ---   OPEC is growing nervous about the continued slide in oilprices. But the group is unlikely to take any action beforelate May, when it holds its regular midyear conference.   ---   Time Warner's long-term public debt was placed on Sandamp;P'sCreditWatch with negative implications due to its financingpact with Pathe.   ---   Massachusetts announced steps to help firms obtain loansamid growing concern that a credit crunch may be worseningthe state's economic woes.   ---   Motorola posted a modest 3.3% in first-quarter earnings,but signs that its computer-chip business is rebounding sentits stock higher.   ---   Westinghouse Electric reported that first-quarter earningsrose 11%, though revenue dropped slightly.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 136,020,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2731.08, up 9.01; transportation 1176.39, up 5.34; utilities213.03, off 1.07.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3327.03, off10.65.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.59, up 0.70; spotindex 134.90, up 0.53.   Dollar: 157.60 yen, off 0.63; 1.6755 marks, off 0.0180.</TEXT></DOC>